(2) A similar view, showing mainly the south side. The building whose side wall is vividly apparent, is No. 423.

(3) A view of the same area shown in No. 1 from a point slightly receded and as in that instance, across Jackson Street. These buildings are being demolished for the Vladeck City Houses, a project financed by the City and its adjoining Vladeck Houses, a USFA sponsored feature. The shells of tenements appearing at the left are at the S.W. corner of Monroe and Jackson Streets.

Corlears Hook Park: A panoramic set of 2 views, westward from the East River, showing this play area that is bounded by Jackson (left), Cherry (background) and Corlears (right) Streets. Upon the latter are two factory structures, one occupied by Hecker Jones, Jewell Milling Co., and the other by the Standard Milling Co. These buildings obscure a view of the Williamsburg Bridge, which is slightly northward.

July 10, 1937.

P. L. Sperr.

(1) Jackson Street, north from and including Cherry, to and including Grand Streets.  Also shown, in the foreground, is the North Western corner of Corlears Hook Park, West side of Street. Corlears Hook Park: A northward view towards Cherry Street from the East River. At the left and right, respectively are Jackson and Corlears Street. On the former, at Madison Street, is the institutional P. S. 12. This appears because of the demolition of several blocks of tenements that formerly would obscure the view. Upon this prepared site will rise the N. Y. City and the U. S. H. A. Houses, the Vladeck City Houses and the Vladeck Houses. Skirting the waters edge will be the East River Drive.

July 28, 1939

Corlears Hook Park: A northward view from the East River shore. In the background are buildings on the marginal Cherry Street, extending from Jackson Street on the left to Corlears Street on the right. The band-stand is in a line with these. Those to the left are to be removed for the N. Y. City built, Vladeck Houses. The new East River Drive will skirt the waters edge.
